<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING BRIEFING: NASTASE RETURNS HOME, FINDS AN UGLY SCENE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GARR KLUENDER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Romanian tennis star Ilie Nastase says his legs shook as he watched people 
being killed by soldiers in Bucharest, Romania, last week. 
</P>
<P>
Nastase gave this account to the Sunday Telegraph after his arrival in London 
Friday: 
</P>
<P>
"On Thursday I had to go to see what was happening. I did not fight but I just 
wanted to be part of what all these people were doing. I was shocked. I saw 
people falling down as soldiers and police opened fire. Then in the evening 
they were firing on them from helicopters." 
</P>
<P>
Nastase, 43, who had "never seen a dead person in my life before," said a tank 
started firing behind him. "I wasn't a normal person, my legs were shaking, 
everything was shaking." 
</P>
<P>
At Bucharest Airport Friday, his flight was delayed because it was feared 
revolutionary forces might shoot it down, Nastase said. 
</P>
<P>
Nastase noted that while he is an officer in the Romanian army, the rank is 
merely honorary, "given to me because of my tennis playing. I don't have any 
links with them." 
</P>
<P>
Nastase, famous for his flamboyant on-court antics, won the 1972 U.S. Open and 
the 1973 French Open. 
</P>
<P>
Trivia time: On Dec. 26, 1955, who passed for two touchdowns and ran for two in 
the Cleveland Browns' 38-14 victory over the Rams for the NFL championship? 
</P>
<P>
There ought to be a law: The Seattle SuperSonics' Xavier McDaniel and Charles 
Oakley of the New York Knicks were fined $7,500 and suspended for one game for 
fighting last week. But the league also fined 13 players $500 each for leaving 
the bench during the brawl, which angered the Sonics' Olden Polynice. 
</P>
<P>
"It's not like the refs were going to break it up," Polynice said. "Those were 
big guys out there. If we didn't break it up, those guys would still be 
fighting." 
</P>
<P>
Helping hand: After learning of an AIDS epidemic in his home of Voskresensk in 
the Soviet Union, Vancouver Canuck center Igor Larionov bought 10,000 syringes 
for its hospital, where up to a dozen patients were said to have been injected 
with the same needle. 
</P>
<P>
Canuck trainer Larry Ashley said: "It's an insight into how much Igor cares for 
his people. A gesture like this shows he has real good qualities." 
</P>
<P>
Trivia answer: Otto Graham. 
</P>
<P>
Quotebook: Entertainer Bob Hope on today's college football players: "I get a 
kick out of how big these guys have become. They should have license plates on 
them." GARR KLUENDER 
</P>
</TEXT>
